<p>I have a table that stores lists of postal/ZIP codes:</p>  <pre><code>CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `postal_codes` (   `id` int(10) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,   `codes` text NOT NULL,   PRIMARY KEY (`id`),   FULLTEXT KEY `codes` (`codes`) ) ENGINE=MyISAM  DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8 AUTO_INCREMENT=3;  INSERT INTO `postal_codes` (`id`, `codes`) VALUES (1, '30301\r\n30302\r\n30303'), (2, '90001\r\n90002\r\n90003\r\n90004\r\n90005'); </code></pre>  <p>I need to check whether a certain row contains a certain postal/ZIP code. However, it doesn't work. For example, this query returns the row with an ID of 2 although the 'codes' column doesn't contain 'dfgdfgdfgdf'. Why is that?</p>  <pre><code>SELECT * FROM postal_codes WHERE MATCH(codes) AGAINST('+dfgdfgdfgdf' IN BOOLEAN MODE) AND id='2' </code></pre>